$_topic{ intro } =
{
    order => 1,
    about => q{Introduction to 'Git for Mortals'},
    help => q{Gim is an attempt at providing users with a nicer
command line interface to the version control software Git.

https://github.com/DevSolar/gim

It was written by Martin Baute, <solar@rootdirectory.de>, and is
provided as free software under Creative Commons CC0 1.0 Universal.

https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/

Gim is written in Perl, and great care has been taken to ensure
that it runs in Git Bash for Windows (which does not cater for
installing additional modules as dependencies). It should run fine
anywhere Git itself runs, including Git Bash, Cygwin, and native
Bash on both Linux and Android.
}};

$_topic{ simplicity } =
{
    order => 2,
    about => q{How Gim tries to be simpler},
    help => q{Git was written as a power tool for repository
maintainers, then got more options for more diverse workflows,
and unfortunately it never received the reworking and polish it
should have.

For one, Git offers extensive pretty-printing options, yet
by default uses rather unappealing formatting on most of its
commands. There is technical data cluttering the output of
e.g. ‘pull’ or ‘push’, unnecessary verboseness to ‘status’,
and the default output of ‘log’ is dismal.

Gim attempts to prune Git output of unnecessary details, to
format output in a way easily skimmed at a glance, and to make
use of colors to improve legibility.

Some frequently used Git functions hide behind somewhat less
than intuitive combinations of commands and options. Plus,
some features of Git are rather confusing to newcomers, both
without previous VCS knowledge and those coming from e.g.
Subversion or Perforce. One example would be the whole concept
of Staging, which Git documentation also refers to as “the
Index File” in places to confuse you even further.

A side effect of this is that Git documentation, like manual
pages or the built-in help, is lengthy, confusing, and quite
often merely cross-referencing yet other documentation. This
can be quite irritating.

Gim trims down (some would say ruthlessly) on the number of
available options, without compromising too much on functionality.
The commands you will be using dozens of times a day should be
short, easily memorized mnemonics without requiring extra options.

Gim has consciously decided to rename some specific commands
to cater for the more common (and less surprising) use case,
e.g. using ‘revert’ to refer to the reverting of local changes,
not reverting commits by making another commit.

Gim provides documentation for all its commands through ‘gim
help’, and tries to keep things short and to the point, so you
can go back to programming as soon as possible.
}};

$_topic{ safety } =
{
    order => 3,
    about => q{How Gim tries to be safer},
    help => q{There are several features to Git that are, to put
it mildly, flirting with desaster. This is because Git, unlike
many other versioning tools, explicitly allows removing or
overwriting information, even from commits that had been made
long ago. Or get you swamped in the middle of a multi-command
workflow with very few hints on what is going on, or how to
recover from there gracefully.

While some of these features are actually quite useful, the way
Git communicates about those -- or rather, does not communicate
in time -- can be daunting. A good rule of thumb for beginners
is to stay away from any command beginning with ‘re...’, and to
use ‘--force’ only after asking someone more experienced.

Gim tries to be more up-forward with information, especially in
multi-command workflows and potentially damaging operations. As
a rule of thumb, Gim will always ask you before doing anything
that might destroy data.

In other areas, Gim combines multi-command workflows into fewer
commands, or even a single one, while adding safeguards and
double-checks to keep you from derailing.
}};

$_topic{ navigation } =
{
    order => 4,
    about => q{Commits, Tags, Branches, Navigation},
    help => q{To understand several more advanced topics, it is
necessary to understand how a repository is being navigated.

Every commit in the repository is identified by a 160-bit hash.
Any existing commit can be addressed by that hash.

Since hash values are somewhat cumbersome, commits that you would
routinely want to navigate to can be tagged with plain text names
for ease of reference. (Check out the ‘gim tag’ subcommand and
the ‘tags’ help topic.)

A branch is a special tag that gets moved along as you make new
commits.

The current commit also can be referred to by a special tag,
‘HEAD’.

Every commit (except the very first one) has at least one “parent”
commit. (Merge commits have more than one.) You can always move
“up” the commit chain along the parental line, but you cannot move
“down”. (A commit knows its parent(s), but not its childs.)

This results in a special case if you navigated to a commit that
is not a branch head: Git can only “see” the current commit
(“HEAD”) and its parents. Git calls this state “detached HEAD”.

Should you make a commit now, that would not be placed “in line”
with any branch, but basically your ‘HEAD’ would now be pointing
at a new branch head that has no name so far.

You can assign a branch name to your current ‘HEAD’ (‘mkbranch’),
or move back to one of the branch heads.
}};

$_topic{ rewrite } =
{
    order => 5,
    about => q{Rewriting history},
    help => q{Certain features of Gim allow overwriting the commit
history. This has pros and cons.

Unneeded branches can be deleted, confusing merge histories can be
cleaned up, and several individual commits can be squashed into
one, to name just a few pros.

There are three significant cons, however.

The information “cleaned up” this way will be lost. And anyone who
has already cloned (or pulled) the previous version(s) might get
confused when the next pull changes the basis for their edits.

And, probably most nefarious of them all, rewriting history wipes
out any tags applied to any of the commits affected by the rewrite.
Basically, if anything is changed about a commit -- including the
hash code of its parent -- it is no longer the commit that had been
tagged, but a different commit, and any tag on it is lost.

Gim draws the line at changing “public” history. While there will
be no extra warnings when you rewrite local history, Gim will warn
and request additional confirmation from you when a command would
affect history that has already been pushed upstream.
}};

$_topic{ workflows } =
{
    order => 6,
    about => q{How Gim tries to help with workflows},
    help => q{Gim documents a number of common workflows. This
is mostly aimed at newcomers, who are not sure how to do things
yet.

There is no claim that these workflows are described in the best
way, let alone the “one right” way. But they are described in a
simple way, in terms of available Gim commands.
}};

$_topic{ tags } =
{
    order => 7,
    about => q{How Gim makes tags useful},
    help => q{THe default behavior of Git when it comes to tags is
somewhat unintuitive, and not really useful. Gim has the proper
options in place to make them useful:

- annotated tags get pushed automatically (but not lightweight
ones).

- annotated tags get pruned on pulling (i.e., annotated tags that
do not exist remotely get removed from your local repository).

- lightweight tags do not get pruned (actually, they are saved and
re-applied during a pull).

This allows you to use annotated tags for sharing tags with others,
and lightweight tags for local use, without requiring any special
attention other than setting or deleting them through ‘gim tag’.

Note that using git commands on your local repository might handle
tags in ways not consistent with this concept. Refer to the git
documentation for details.
}};

